      <h2>Why Men Need a Gender-Specific Multivitamin</h2>

      <p>Men's nutritional requirements are fundamentally different from women's, yet the majority of men either take no multivitamin at all or default to a generic one-size-fits-all formula. This is a mistake. Male physiology demands higher zinc intake for testosterone production and prostate health, less iron (excess iron causes oxidative damage in men), more selenium for prostate cancer prevention, and higher B-vitamin doses to support the greater caloric expenditure associated with typically higher muscle mass and metabolic rates.</p>

      <p>The consequences of ignoring these differences are measurable. The National Institutes of Health reports that <strong>42% of American men are vitamin D deficient</strong> — a nutrient critical for testosterone synthesis, bone density, and immune function. Zinc deficiency, which is directly correlated with low testosterone in clinical studies, affects an estimated 12% of the U.S. population, with higher rates among men who exercise intensely (zinc is lost through sweat). Magnesium deficiency affects roughly 50% of Americans and impairs muscle recovery, sleep quality, and cardiovascular function.</p>

      <p>A well-formulated <strong>men's gummy multivitamin</strong> addresses these specific gaps. Compared to generic multivitamins, men-specific formulas provide optimized zinc (11mg vs. the 8mg in women's formulas), exclude iron (which most men do not need and which can be harmful in excess), include selenium and lycopene for prostate health, and deliver higher B-vitamin doses for energy metabolism. The best formulas go further with omega-3 fatty acids for cardiovascular health and CoQ10 for mitochondrial energy production.</p>

      <p>We purchased 30+ men's gummy multivitamins, analyzed their formulations against NIH Recommended Dietary Allowances for men aged 19-50, consulted registered dietitians, and evaluated taste, texture, and tolerability. Here are the 10 that earned our recommendation.</p>
