      <h2>How We Tested These Men's Gummy Vitamins</h2>

      <div class="tested-box">
        <h3>Our Testing Methodology</h3>
        <p>We applied GummyGuide's standardized testing protocol to every men's gummy multivitamin on this list. Our goal is simple: identify the products that deliver real nutritional value for men, not marketing hype.</p>

        <ol>
          <li><strong>Procurement:</strong> Every product was purchased at full retail price from Amazon, Target, Walmart, or the brand's direct website. We accepted no free samples, sponsorships, or early-access products. Our editorial independence is non-negotiable.</li>
          <li><strong>Nutrient Analysis:</strong> Each formula was evaluated against NIH Recommended Dietary Allowances (RDAs) for men aged 19-50, with particular attention to zinc (11mg), selenium (55mcg), vitamin D (1000+ IU), and B-complex dosing. We verified that men's formulas appropriately exclude or minimize iron.</li>
          <li><strong>Third-Party Verification:</strong> We confirmed all testing claims by checking USP, NSF, USDA Organic, and Non-GMO Project certification databases directly. Unverifiable claims were flagged.</li>
          <li><strong>Taste and Tolerability:</strong> A panel of 20 men evaluated each product for flavor, texture, aftertaste, and gastrointestinal tolerance over a 3-week period. Products that caused nausea, bloating, or unpleasant aftertaste were penalized.</li>
          <li><strong>Value Calculation:</strong> Total cost was divided by the number of servings and weighed against nutrient density. A $12 multivitamin with solid coverage scored higher than a $35 product with equivalent gaps.</li>
          <li><strong>Men-Specific Formulation:</strong> We assessed whether each product was genuinely formulated for men (optimized zinc, selenium, no excess iron) or simply a rebranded generic multivitamin. Products with authentic men-specific formulations scored higher.</li>
        </ol>

        <p>Products were scored on a weighted scale: Nutrient Coverage (30%), Men-Specific Formulation (20%), Third-Party Testing (15%), Taste and Tolerability (15%), Value (15%), and Brand Transparency (5%). Rankings reflect these composite scores.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- What to Look For -->
    <section>
      <h2>What to Look for in a Men's Gummy Multivitamin</h2>

      <div class="ing-box">
        <h3>Essential Nutrients Every Men's Formula Should Include</h3>
        <p>Men's nutritional needs change with age, activity level, and health goals. Here are the nutrients that should be non-negotiable in any men's gummy multivitamin:</p>

        <ul>
          <li><strong>Zinc (11mg):</strong> Essential for testosterone synthesis, immune function, and wound healing. Zinc deficiency is directly correlated with low testosterone in clinical studies. Men who exercise intensely lose additional zinc through sweat, making supplementation particularly important for active men.</li>
          <li><strong>Vitamin D3 (1000-2000 IU):</strong> Functions as a hormone precursor with documented effects on testosterone levels, bone density, immune function, and mood regulation. The NIH reports that 42% of American adults are vitamin D deficient, with rates even higher among men who work indoors.</li>
          <li><strong>Selenium (55mcg):</strong> Supports thyroid function and has been studied extensively for its potential role in prostate cancer prevention. The Nutritional Prevention of Cancer trial found that selenium supplementation reduced prostate cancer incidence by 63% in men with low baseline selenium levels.</li>
          <li><strong>B Vitamins (B6, B12, Niacin):</strong> Support energy metabolism, red blood cell production, and neurological function. B12 deficiency becomes more common with age as stomach acid production decreases, impairing B12 absorption from food.</li>
          <li><strong>Magnesium:</strong> Supports muscle function, sleep quality, and cardiovascular health. Approximately 50% of Americans consume inadequate magnesium, and deficiency is associated with increased muscle cramps, poor sleep, and elevated blood pressure.</li>
          <li><strong>No Excess Iron:</strong> Men's multivitamins should contain little to no iron. Unlike menstruating women, men lose minimal iron through normal physiology, and excess iron accumulation is associated with oxidative damage, liver disease, and cardiovascular risk.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Bonus Ingredients for Men Over 30</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>CoQ10:</strong> Natural CoQ10 production declines after age 30. Supplementation supports mitochondrial energy production in the heart, brain, and muscles.</li>
          <li><strong>Lycopene:</strong> The carotenoid found in tomatoes has been associated with reduced prostate cancer risk in multiple large-scale observational studies.</li>
          <li><strong>Omega-3 (EPA/DHA):</strong> Supports cardiovascular health, reduces inflammation, and supports cognitive function. The American Heart Association recommends 250-500mg combined EPA/DHA daily.</li>
          <li><strong>Lutein:</strong> Supports macular health, protecting against age-related vision loss — the leading cause of blindness in older men.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

